    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>Water sampling</title>
            <para>Several grab samples at discrete depths from the surface to bottom of lake. If in the “Sample” column the value has an “f” after it, the sample was filtered through 30µm mesh for an edible or small algae chlorophyll-a estimate</para>
          </section>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>Lab method</title>
            <para>EPA method 445.0 – “Samples were filtered on to Whatman GF/F filters (Whatman, Brentford,UK) and analyzed for chl a concentrations, corrected for pheopigments on a Turner Designs TD-700 fluorometer (Turner Designs, Sunnyvale, California, USA; Marker et al. 1980) following Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) method 445.0. Fluorometer regularly calibrated and duplicates are not run.</para>
          </section>
        </description>
        <instrumentation>fluorometer</instrumentation>
      </methodStep>
      <sampling>
        <studyExtent>
          <description>
            <para>Inland lakes in CT, USA
6 long-term lakes
13 other lakes</para>
          </description>
        </studyExtent>
        <samplingDescription>
          <para>The long term study lakes are sampled every other week during the ice off season (May-Dec). Note that sampling is not necessarily consistent and samples may not have been collected every 2-3 weeks for all lakes. There is only data after 2010 for Linsley lake as they are behind on data analysis. The other 13 lakes included in this data set were sampled only during the summer of 2004 or summer of 2005</para>
        </samplingDescription>
      </sampling>
    </methods>
